WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.340
 Hello, and welcome to a walkthrough for Django for Everybody.

00:00:05.340 --> 00:00:08.140
 So the walkthrough that we're going to be doing

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:11.780
 is the walkthrough for the My Articles, which

00:00:11.780 --> 00:00:16.120
 is really focusing on the notion of owning rows in a model.

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:20.000
 And what I've got going here is I'm logged in twice.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.960
 I'm logged in one with a user ID of one,

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:24.840
 and the other is a user ID of two.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:28.600
 So let's just do a quick demonstration of what really

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:30.960
 owning rows in a model is.

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:33.720
 So here I'm logged in as my first user, and now I'm logged in.

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:36.400
 I'm using a separate browser, because this is Safari

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:38.800
 and this is Firefox.

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:41.240
 You can't just do this with tabs, because the cookies

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:42.400
 are shared between tabs.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.840
 And so you can log in and log out.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:49.160
 I want to just be logged in simultaneously, OK?

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.200
 And so I've got two of these tabs.

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:54.400
 Refresh.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:58.440
 So you'll notice that the Edit and Delete buttons show up

00:00:58.440 --> 00:00:59.880
 differently for different users.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:03.560
 And that's because this row in the table Lawnmower

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:07.000
 belongs to this user, user number two.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.480
 And these two rows belong to this user.

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:12.400
 So if I take a look at administration

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:18.520
 and I go down into Groups-- oh, not groups, not groups--

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:24.640
 Users, I can kind of hover figure out that CSEV is two.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:26.920
 You can kind of see at the bottom there.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:30.360
 And djfurry is user one, and CSEV is user number two.

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:35.920
 So those are the primary keys in Django's user table.

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:39.120
 And now if I go and I take a look at these articles,

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:41.240
 you will see-- and this looks a lot

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:43.920
 like if you were looking at, say, your autos.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:49.560
 Here's the rows or the models in articles.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:52.320
 And if I look at Lawnmower, you see that there is a title,

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.000
 some text, and the owner is a dropdown.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.040
 And that's because this is a one-to-many field.

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:01.260
 This is a one-to-many field between the articles

00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:02.280
 and the users.

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:07.480
 And then if I switch to a different-- so that's CSEV.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:15.040
 So CSEV owns the lawnmower.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.600
 I must be-- I'm logged in as djfurry here.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:19.480
 No, here.

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:21.640
 That's my name on djfurry.

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:25.280
 And if I switch to Trombone, we'll

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:27.840
 see that that one belongs to djfurry.

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:32.720
 Now I can sit and edit this in Admin.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.080
 But that's not the point.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:37.400
 The point is to build software.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.320
 If you'll notice, when I create a new article,

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.960
 it doesn't ask me what user it was.

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:46.800
 So this is where you would say Dodge or whatever

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:47.840
 when you were doing cars.

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:59.180
 So this is like a race car, slightly used, Neon.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:04.480
 So now I have another one.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:07.040
 And so the key thing was is it looks

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:11.840
 like a create from things we've done before.

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:14.280
 If I look at my articles, here's this.

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:17.160
 But somehow, magically, this owner field is populated.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.640
 And that's the essence of owned rows,

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:23.440
 is we've got a row, a column.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.520
 And these are marked.

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:26.960
 And we know in all our code.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:28.880
 We know the difference, for example,

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.120
 between things we own and things we don't own.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:35.080
 So if I hit refresh over here, there's

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:43.280
 a slightly used race car, but I can't edit it.

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:45.840
 So that's the ownership.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:47.940
 Now, I don't know where to start.

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:49.600
 There's a lot to cover here.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:53.280
 Let me show you-- I don't know.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:55.960
 OK, I'll just start with-- where do we always start?

00:03:55.960 --> 00:03:58.440
 Let's start with-- I'm running this locally.

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:00.520
 I don't know if that bug is there.

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:01.800
 That's not a bug.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:05.800
 So this just looks kind of like your autos.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:07.440
 If you look at it, it looks pretty much

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:08.040
 like the autos.

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:10.680
 I might add a mileage or price in there or something.

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:13.480
 The only thing that's really different at all is this.

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:14.480
 There's a foreign key.

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:18.040
 Now, in your autos, you have a foreign key to makes.

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:21.280
 And the key difference here-- the only thing that's new

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:24.320
 is this idea of where the foreign key is pointing at.

00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:29.280
 Now, the problem is in Django, there is actually a table

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:31.400
 that all these users live in.

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:35.000
 And I can probably come over here and type .tables.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:35.760
 And I can see it.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:37.440
 I think it's probably here.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:45.360
 So let's just try saying, select star from auth user.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:47.760
 So we should see a bunch of rows.

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:49.560
 And so there are my users.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.160
 csev-- it's all jammed together in DJ4E.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:56.440
 So this is row one for DJ4E and csev.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:59.480
 So there is a table and a model.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.320
 The difference is we're not allowed

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:08.080
 to know that this is the user model in the auth application.

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:09.840
 And so what happens is we have to let

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:12.360
 Django tell us what the name of that model is.

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:17.120
 And so we go into settings, which is settings.py, actually.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:19.680
 And we're going to pull in the settings.py.

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:22.000
 And the default is auth user model.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.800
 And that's the name of the model.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:26.520
 And so this is a foreign key to a place

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:29.720
 that we don't exactly know, but Django will tell us

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:30.920
 and put in a string here.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:33.720
 If we were to print this out, we would see what that is.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:36.360
 That's just a string, but it's not a string we mess with.

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:38.840
 On delete cascade, that's just normal.

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:42.600
 The kind of parent row, the one row is in users.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:44.520
 And if you delete a user, that means

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:46.840
 that all of the rows that belong to that user

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:48.880
 will get deleted because on delete cascade.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.600
 I'm choosing that as the model.

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:57.400
 And so you see, created ad, if we go back into the--

00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:59.400
 you see all of these things.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:01.760
 Now created ad, admin doesn't show.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:04.160
 It's pretty smart knowing about created ad and update.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.640
 So it doesn't bother doing that, and it actually

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.200
 updates them automatically.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:11.560
 So it knows something about created ad and updated ad

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:14.520
 in admin.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:18.640
 So that is our model.

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:23.880
 If we were to take a look at myarts.Article,

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.840
 you will see that there is a foreign key right there.

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:29.320
 There's a foreign key.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:37.120
 And if we say select star from myarts.Article,

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:40.640
 we will see that there is a foreign key in there.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:42.400
 So this row belongs to user one.

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:43.680
 This row belongs to user one.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.360
 That row belongs to user two.

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:47.120
 And that row belongs to user one,

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:49.560
 which is perfectly reflected here.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:53.040
 So now I am user one, so I can edit three of them.

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:55.760
 Now I am here with user two, and I can edit one of them.

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:58.560
 So I'm editing the ones where I own it.

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:01.560
 So ultimately, we're going to write a bunch of code

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:04.280
 so that these numbers are properly updated.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:09.760
 So when you add the article, it works the way you want to work.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:13.080
 So let's just take a look at urls.py.

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:14.520
 It's pretty boring.

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:16.560
 This looks just like autos.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:19.960
 I probably hoisted up success URL here,

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:23.680
 put that in the as view as a parameter.

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:28.160
 And so that makes my views even simpler.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:31.000
 myarts.all points to that view.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.680
 I think it actually is kind of prettier

00:07:32.680 --> 00:07:37.600
 to put it in here, because this is sort of a URL place.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:38.720
 And so it's not in my view.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.600
 So that makes my views really succinct.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:49.520
 And so it's like what you did once you got your autos down

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:53.720
 to just using the generics.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.880
 And so I have a list, a detail, a create, an update,

00:07:56.880 --> 00:07:58.720
 and a delete.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.840
 And I have a model called article, which I just showed you.

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:06.560
 And I am going to reuse some general purpose views

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:08.240
 for owner kinds of rows.

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:10.960
 Now, these are not from Django.

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:12.440
 These are from me.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:13.680
 I made them.

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:15.360
 And now I'm using them.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:18.800
 So article list view extends owner list view.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:21.760
 And then I can put all my things in there.

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:25.320
 The success URL, actually, I don't need that here.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:28.880
 But for create view, I do need a success URL.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:33.080
 But for create view, that success URL comes right from here.

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:34.840
 So I could have put it either here,

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:36.240
 or I could have put it here.

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:38.520
 For me, just kind of after a while,

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:41.240
 I think this is prettier, because now I

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:44.600
 can look at all the names of my arts, et cetera.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:45.720
 So that's kind of nice.

00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:48.160
 OK.

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:49.280
 So here's views.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:50.760
 We're going to come back to this.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:54.200
 All the brains of this operation are in owner list view, owner

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:56.280
 detail view, create view, update view.

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:57.880
 And we'll look at that last.

00:08:57.880 --> 00:09:00.080
 So that's where the hardest part is.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:03.840
 But let's first look at the template.

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:07.040
 And so here's the template.

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:09.520
 This looks a lot like your autos.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.560
 The only real difference here is that this edit and delete

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:17.240
 button is inside of an if statement.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:21.400
 So it's article update, article ID, article delete, article ID.

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:22.080
 That's the same.

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:23.880
 You've done that, right?

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:27.040
 But all it says is if article.owner

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:28.720
 is equal to the current logged in user.

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:31.760
 Article.owner is one of the article lists.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:33.320
 And that's just one of the fields

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:36.160
 in the model, which happens to be a number.

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:39.360
 But we're giving this user for free, right?

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:42.560
 It just hands us user, and so we can compare it.

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:47.680
 So if this is one that we own, we show this link.

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:50.640
 And if it's not one that we own, we don't show the link, right?

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:53.360
 So we don't show the link for the ones that we own.

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:57.880
 Now, I hope by now you realize that merely not--

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:02.120
 we have to also protect, right?

00:10:02.120 --> 00:10:05.520
 So this is number four, right?

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:08.520
 And if I click Edit, number five.

00:10:08.520 --> 00:10:11.240
 But what if I just change this to four?

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:15.880
 We still-- just not putting up the link

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:20.040
 does not mean that we can't have something go to that link.

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:22.640
 So I'm cheating by putting in this link

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:24.120
 if this is going to blow up, right?

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:28.640
 And so we'll show you how just because you don't put the link

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:30.800
 up doesn't mean that people can't go to the link.

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:32.880
 They can guess what the link is.

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:34.360
 I just did that.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:36.680
 I went to an article I could update.

00:10:36.680 --> 00:10:40.800
 I noticed the primary key of one I could not update to be four.

00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:43.560
 And then I went to five, and then I just edited it,

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:46.400
 changed it to four, and I attempted to update four.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:49.640
 So it's not good enough just to not show the link.

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:51.120
 That's actually not security.

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:52.600
 That just is prettiness.

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:53.640
 Usability.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:56.120
 Don't show a link that is going to blow up if you click on it.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:59.520
 So that's not really protecting us.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:01.720
 This if statement is not really protecting us

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:05.440
 from clicking on or attempting to go edit or delete.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:09.720
 It's just not showing it if it's not going to work.

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:11.000
 OK.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.680
 And again, article.owner is just a column in this model.

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.160
 And user is the current logged in user.

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:18.640
 OK?

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:23.560
 OK.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:27.360
 So what we'd seen before is I would create a view

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:31.400
 and then use it in my urls.py, and it would extend another view.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:33.360
 So now it's time to take a look at where

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:36.480
 this view is being defined.

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:39.920
 And so here's our view, generic view, the New York list view,

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:41.040
 delete view.

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:42.600
 These are the generic ones.

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:44.440
 And all I'm really doing here is I'm

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:48.960
 creating a class called owner list view that extends list view.

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:53.040
 Now, it pulls in everything that list view is.

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.680
 And you'll notice I've added nothing to it.

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:59.920
 And I really could, because the list view doesn't really care.

00:11:59.920 --> 00:12:02.440
 It's not really doing anything other than the fact

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:04.760
 that that value is in the models.

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.680
 So it's going to come in.

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:08.920
 So I could have made this be list view,

00:12:08.920 --> 00:12:10.480
 but I just want it to be pretty.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:13.480
 I want to make it so that I could just say owner list view,

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:15.200
 owner detail view.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:18.720
 And so you'll notice that I'm not making any changes

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:20.520
 at the moment of inheritance.

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:22.120
 I'm not changing owner.

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:24.760
 So owner list view is exactly the same as list view.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.840
 And owner detail is exactly the same as detail.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:30.800
 I just did it to make it pretty in case later on,

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:32.920
 maybe I want to add some.

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:35.760
 But now we get to owner create view.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:41.200
 Owner create view is something that matters a lot.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.600
 So there's two things we've got to do for owner create view.

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:47.960
 So let's go ahead and start to add an article.

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:51.080
 So the first thing is is there is no field here

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:53.840
 for which user it is.

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:55.960
 It would be kind of silly.

00:12:55.960 --> 00:13:00.640
 And I can actually mess this up.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:09.280
 So if I go to create view here and I add user,

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:15.640
 and if I hit refresh on the create view, come on, back up.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:18.400
 Oh, it's not user.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:18.880
 Owner.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:25.040
 So if I add it to that list-- and part of this,

00:13:25.040 --> 00:13:29.920
 what's going on here, is there is both a model and a form.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:33.040
 This fields equals is informing the form.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:35.640
 And the form is the user interface.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:37.160
 So look at this.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:40.080
 I'm allowing the user to specify it.

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:42.080
 And now they can set the owner.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:43.240
 Pretty convenient.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:44.800
 Well, that's not what we want.

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:48.120
 So that's why, in this create view,

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:50.720
 you say, don't let them set the owner.

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:52.100
 I don't want them to see the owner.

00:13:52.100 --> 00:13:54.480
 Because it takes a little while for this thing to restart.

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:55.640
 OK, now it's restarted.

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:57.040
 And I can hit refresh.

00:13:57.040 --> 00:13:57.920
 So it was blowing up.

00:13:57.920 --> 00:14:00.840
